[assistant] 抽取并记录信息: {"other_info": "The provided information describes a systematic review process focused on clinical trials related to dementia and cognitive impairment. Below is an organized summary of the key aspects of this process:\n\n### **Search Strategy**\n- **Databases and Resources**: The search was conducted across multiple databases, including MEDLINE, EMBASE, PsycINFO, CINAHL, LILACS, and specialized registers (e.g., ClinicalTrials.gov, ISRCTN).\n- **Sources**: Information was extracted from clinical trial registries such as the National Health Service Clinical Trials Register, ReFeR, Current Controlled Trials (mRCT), and others.\n- **Ongoing Trials Database**: The IPFMA Clinical Trials Register was used alongside controlled trials databases like CenterWatch.\n\n### **Study Selection**\n- **Initial Search**: References were identified through automated searches in academic databases and registers. These were then reviewed manually for relevance.\n- **Exclusion/Inclusion Criteria**: Studies were excluded or included based on predefined criteria, with additional information sought from study authors if necessary.\n- **Consensus**: Review authors reached a final consensus after independent assessments.\n\n### **Data Extraction**\n- **Continuous Data**: For outcomes measured using ordinal rating scales with more than 10 categories, data was treated as continuous. Summary statistics (mean change from baseline, standard error, number of patients) were extracted for each treatment group and time point.\n- **Binary Data**: The number of participants in each treatment group and those experiencing the outcome of interest were sought.\n\n### **Data Analysis**\n- **Ordinal Rating Scales**: Outcomes often arose from scales with many categories (more than 10), treated as continuous data assuming normal distribution.\n- **Missing Data Handling**: When baseline results were unavailable, changes from baseline were calculated using baseline and post-treatment means and standard deviations, assuming a zero correlation between measurements.\n\n### **Quality Assessment**\n- **Randomization and Blinding**: Methods used in each trial were assessed for aspects like randomization techniques, blinding, patient selection, control group methods, reporting of results, and statistical analysis quality.\n  \nThis systematic approach aimed to compile comprehensive data on clinical trials related to dementia and cognitive impairment, ensuring a thorough and methodical review process."}
